Chet,<br><br>
I think that there are peaks and valleys on this site, just as there were in Vietnam and in life in general. During the various stages of this, site different people were more prominent than others - depending on the subject matter.<br><br>
The stage we are in now is definitely not for the faint of heart.<br><br>
The so called regulars of late are types who have very strong personalities which match their opinionated postings.<br><br>
Our purpose in posting should not be so much in trying to find the &quot;resolutions&quot; you refer to as it is should be presenting the various sides of a terribly complex issue. Resolutions would be nice, but are they attainable?<br><br>
Once opinionss have been expressed and gone over, then it can be left to the reader (it is mindboggling to think of the number of possible lurkers) to decide and to form an opinion of his own.<br><br>
You have mentioned living in a very historic section of Virginia. Just look at the number of people who are Civil War buffs - well over a hundred years after its occurance. My hope is that today there will be a growing numbers of people who will become interested in our war - why it was fought AND why it was protested. All here have put forth much effort with our individual oral histories, to provide a treasure trove for those who seek answers!<br><br>
We may have not provided &quot;resolutions&quot;, but we have ACCOMPLISHED a great deal, all the same. <br><br>
The resolutions may have to come from the following generations, who will *resolve* to never allow a Vietnam ever occur again - and that is in everone's interest - no matter what their vantage point.
